[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] In software engineering, **code coverage**, also called **test coverage**, is a percentage measure of the degree to which the source code of a program is executed when a particular test suite is run.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] A program with high code coverage has more of its source code executed during testing, which suggests it has a lower chance of containing undetected software bugs compared to a program with low code coverage.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] Many different metrics can be used to calculate test coverage.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] Some of the most basic are the percentage of program subroutines and the percentage of program statements called during execution of the test suite.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] Code coverage was among the first methods invented for systematic software testing.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] The first published reference was by Miller and Maloney in *Communications of the ACM*, in 1963.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] To measure what percentage of code has been executed by a test suite, one or more *coverage criteria* are used.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] These are usually defined as rules or requirements, which a test suite must satisfy.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] Assume this function is a part of some bigger program and this program was run with some test suite.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] In programming languages that do not perform short-circuit evaluation, condition coverage does not necessarily imply branch coverage.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] However, this set of tests does not satisfy branch coverage since neither case will meet the `if` condition.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] Fault injection may be necessary to ensure that all conditions and branches of exception-handling code have adequate coverage during testing.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] A combination of function coverage and branch coverage is sometimes also called **decision coverage**.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] This criterion requires that every point of entry and exit in the program has been invoked at least once, and every decision in the program has taken on all possible outcomes at least once.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] In this context, the decision is a Boolean expression comprising conditions and zero or more Boolean operators.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] This definition is not the same as branch coverage, however, the term *decision coverage* is sometimes used as a synonym for it.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] However, the above tests set will not satisfy modified condition/decision coverage, since in the first test, the value of 'b' and in the second test the value of 'c' would not influence the output.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] This criterion requires that all combinations of conditions inside each decision are tested.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] Safety-critical or dependable applications are often required to demonstrate 100% of some form of test coverage.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] For example, the ECSS-E-ST-40C standard demands 100% statement and decision coverage for two out of four different criticality levels; for the other ones, target coverage values are up to negotiation between supplier and customer.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] Some of the coverage criteria above are connected.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] For instance, path coverage implies decision, statement and entry/exit coverage.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] Decision coverage implies statement coverage, because every statement is part of a branch.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] Full path coverage, of the type described above, is usually impractical or impossible.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] Any module with a succession of n decisions in it can have up to $2^{n}$ paths within it; loop constructs can result in an infinite number of paths.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] Many paths may also be infeasible, in that there is no input to the program under test that can cause that particular path to be executed.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] However, a general-purpose algorithm for identifying infeasible paths has been proven to be impossible (such an algorithm could be used to solve the halting problem).
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] Basis path testing is for instance a method of achieving complete branch coverage without achieving complete path coverage.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] Methods for practical path coverage testing instead attempt to identify classes of code paths that differ only in the number of loop executions, and to achieve "basis path" coverage the tester must cover all the path classes.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] The target software is built with special options or libraries and run under a controlled environment, to map every executed function to the function points in the source code.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] This allows testing parts of the target software that are rarely or never accessed under normal conditions, and helps reassure that the most important conditions (function points) have been tested.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] The resulting output is then analyzed to see what areas of code have not been exercised and the tests are updated to include these areas as necessary.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] Combined with other test coverage methods, the aim is to develop a rigorous, yet manageable, set of regression tests.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] Software authors can look at test coverage results to devise additional tests and input or configuration sets to increase the coverage over vital functions.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] Two common forms of test coverage are statement (or line) coverage and branch (or edge) coverage.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] Line coverage reports on the execution footprint of testing in terms of which lines of code were executed to complete the test.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] Edge coverage reports which branches or code decision points were executed to complete the test.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] They both report a coverage metric, measured as a percentage.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] The meaning of this depends on what form(s) of coverage have been used, as 67% branch coverage is more comprehensive than 67% statement coverage.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] Generally, test coverage tools incur computation and logging in addition to the actual program thereby slowing down the application, so typically this analysis is not done in production.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] As one might expect, there are classes of software that cannot be feasibly subjected to these coverage tests, though a degree of coverage mapping can be approximated through analysis rather than direct testing.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] There are also some sorts of defects which are affected by such tools.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] In particular, some race conditions or similar real time sensitive operations can be masked when run under test environments; though conversely, some of these defects may become easier to find as a result of the additional overhead of the testing code.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] Most professional software developers use C1 and C2 coverage.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] C1 stands for statement coverage and C2 for branch or condition coverage.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] With a combination of C1 and C2, it is possible to cover most statements in a code base.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] Statement coverage would also cover function coverage with entry and exit, loop, path, state flow, control flow and data flow coverage.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] With these methods, it is possible to achieve nearly 100% code coverage in most software projects.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] Test coverage is one consideration in the safety certification of avionics equipment.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] The guidelines by which avionics gear is certified by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) is documented in DO-178B and DO-178C.
[src:mutation-testing/code-coverage] Test coverage is also a requirement in part 6 of the automotive safety standard ISO 26262 *Road Vehicles - Functional Safety*.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] In computer science, **fault injection** is a testing technique for understanding how computing systems behave when stressed in unusual ways.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] This can be achieved using physical- or software-based means, or using a hybrid approach.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] Widely studied physical fault injections include the application of high voltages, extreme temperatures and electromagnetic pulses on electronic components, such as computer memory and central processing units.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] By exposing components to conditions beyond their intended operating limits, computing systems can be coerced into mis-executing instructions and corrupting critical data.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] In software testing, fault injection is a technique for improving the coverage of a test by introducing faults to test code paths; in particular error handling code paths, that might otherwise rarely be followed.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] It is often used with stress testing and is widely considered to be an important part of developing robust software.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] Robustness testing (also known as syntax testing, fuzzing or fuzz testing) is a type of fault injection commonly used to test for vulnerabilities in communication interfaces such as protocols, command line parameters, or APIs.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] The propagation of a fault through to an observable failure follows a well-defined cycle.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] When executed, a fault may cause an error, which is an invalid state within a system boundary.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] An error may cause further errors within the system boundary, therefore each new error acts as a fault, or it may propagate to the system boundary and be observable.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] When error states are observed at the system boundary they are termed failures.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] This mechanism is termed the fault-error-failure cycle and is a key mechanism in dependability.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] The technique of fault injection dates back to the 1970s when it was first used to induce faults at a hardware level.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] This type of fault injection is called Hardware Implemented Fault Injection (HWIFI) and attempts to simulate hardware failures within a system.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] The first experiments in hardware fault involved nothing more than shorting connections on circuit boards and observing the effect on the system (bridging faults).
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] It was used primarily as a test of the dependability of the hardware system.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] Later specialised hardware was developed to extend this technique, such as devices to bombard specific areas of a circuit board with heavy radiation.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] It was soon found that faults could be induced by software techniques and that aspects of this technique could be useful for assessing software systems.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] Collectively these techniques are known as Software Implemented Fault Injection (SWIFI).
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] SWIFI techniques can be categorized into two types: compile-time injection and runtime injection.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] Code mutation produces faults which are very similar to those unintentionally added by programmers.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] A refinement of code mutation is *Code Insertion Fault Injection* which adds code, rather than modifying existing code.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] In this case, pFunc is the perturbation function and it is applied to the return value of the function that has been called introducing a fault into the system.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] Runtime injection techniques can use a number of different techniques to insert faults into a system via a trigger.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] These techniques are often based around the debugging facilities provided by computer processor architectures.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] Fuzzing is an especially useful form of Black-box testing since the various invalid inputs that are submitted to the software system do not depend on, and are not created based on knowledge of, the details of the code running inside the system.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] This technique is based on a nail bed, necessary to contact the electronics of the products, where a specific test pad has been left free (Design for testability of PCB), and properly inject disturbance signals, in order to see the product's control- reaction arm's reaction if present.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] It's a technique often used to certify and validate reaction to fault in high reliability products, where safety is involved (Military, Medical, Autonomous vehicle).
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] Because of the wide complexity a dedicated and complex tools is necessary.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] These parameters create the fault space realm.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] The fault space realm will increase exponentially by increasing system complexity.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] Therefore, the traditional fault injection method will not be applicable to use in the modern cyber-physical systems, because they will be so slow, and they will find a small number of faults (less fault coverage).
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] Hence, the testers need an efficient algorithm to choose critical faults that have a higher impact on system behavior.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] Thus, the main research question is how to find critical faults in the fault space realm which have catastrophic effects on system behavior.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] Here are some methods that can aid fault injection to efficiently explore the fault space to reach higher fault coverage in less simulation time.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] Although these types of faults can be injected by hand the possibility of introducing an unintended fault is high, so tools exist to parse a program automatically and insert faults.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] A number of SWIFI Tools have been developed and a selection of these tools is given here.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] Six commonly used fault injection tools are Ferrari, FTAPE, Doctor, Orchestra, Xception and Grid-FIT.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] In contrast to traditional mutation testing where mutant faults are generated and injected into the code description of the model, application of a series of newly defined mutation operators directly to the model properties rather than to the model code has also been investigated.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] Mutant properties that are generated from the initial properties (or test cases) and validated by the model checker should be considered as new properties that have been missed during the initial verification procedure.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] Therefore, adding these newly identified properties to the existing list of properties improves the coverage metric of the formal verification and consequently lead to a more reliable design.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] In the testing of operating systems for example, fault injection is often performed by a *driver* (kernel-mode software) that intercepts *system calls* (calls into the kernel) and randomly returning a failure for some of the calls.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] This type of fault injection is useful for testing low-level user-mode software.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] For higher level software, various methods inject faults.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] In managed code, it is common to use instrumentation.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] Although fault injection can be undertaken by hand, a number of fault injection tools exist to automate the process of fault injection.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] Depending on the complexity of the API for the level where faults are injected, fault injection tests often must be carefully designed to minimize the number of false positives.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] Even a well designed fault injection test can sometimes produce situations that are impossible in the normal operation of the software.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] For example, imagine there are two API functions, `Commit` and `PrepareForCommit`, such that alone, each of these functions can possibly fail, but if `PrepareForCommit` is called and succeeds, a subsequent call to `Commit` is guaranteed to succeed.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] Often, it will be infeasible for the fault injection implementation to keep track of enough state to make the guarantee that the API functions make.
[src:mutation-testing/fault-injection] In this example, a fault injection test of the above code might hit the assert, whereas this would never happen in normal operation.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Mutant creation is done using well-defined *mutation operators* that either mimic typical programming errors (such as using the wrong operator or variable name) or force the creation of valuable tests (such as dividing each expression by zero).
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Mutation testing is a form of white-box testing.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Its purpose is to help the tester develop effective regression tests by locating weaknesses in the test data used to test the program and discovering sections of the tested program's code that are seldom or never accessed during execution.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Most of this article is about "program mutation", in which the program is modified.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] A more general definition of *mutation analysis* is using well-defined rules defined on syntactic structures to make systematic changes to software artifacts.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Mutation analysis has been applied to other problems, but is usually applied to testing.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] So *mutation testing* is defined as using mutation analysis to design new software tests or to evaluate existing software tests.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Thus, mutation analysis and testing can be applied to design models, specifications, databases, tests, XML, and other types of software artifacts, although program mutation is the most common.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Tests can be created to verify the correctness of the implementation of a given software system, but the creation of tests still poses the question of whether the tests are correct and sufficiently cover the requirements associated with the implementation.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] The idea behind mutation testing is that the program being tested works as intended, so if a mutant is introduced and functionality changes this means a bug is introduced, which the tests should then find.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] If a mutant is not detected by the test suite, this typically indicates that the test suite is unable to locate the faults represented by the mutant, but it can also indicate that the mutation introduces no faults.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] That is, the mutation is a valid change, one that either produces a desired result or one that does not affect functionality.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] One (common) way a mutant can be valid is that the code that has been changed is "dead code" that is never executed.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] For mutation testing to function at scale, a large number of mutants are usually introduced, leading to the compilation and execution of an extremely large number of copies of the program.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] This problem of the expense of mutation testing had reduced its practical use as a method of software testing.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] However, the increased use of object-oriented programming languages and unit testing frameworks has led to the creation of mutation testing tools that test individual portions of an application.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Mutation testing was originally proposed by Richard Lipton as a student in 1971, and first developed and published by DeMillo, Lipton and Sayward.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] The first implementation of a mutation testing tool was by Timothy Budd as part of his PhD work (titled *Mutation Analysis*) in 1980 from Yale University.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] (now part of Synopsys) extended many of the principles into the hardware verification domain.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Whereas mutation analysis only expects to detect a difference in the output produced, Certess extends this by verifying that a checker in the testbench will actually detect the difference.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] This extension means that all three stages of verification, namely: activation, propagation, and detection are evaluated.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] They called this functional qualification.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Fuzzing can be considered to be a special case of mutation testing.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] In fuzzing, the messages or data exchanged inside communication interfaces (both inside and between software instances) are mutated to catch failures or differences in processing the data.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Codenomicon (2001) and Mu Dynamics (2005) evolved fuzzing concepts to a fully stateful mutation testing platform, complete with monitors for thoroughly exercising protocol implementations.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Mutation testing is based on two hypotheses.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] The first is the *competent programmer* hypothesis.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] This hypothesis states that competent programmers write programs that are close to being correct.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] "Close" is intended to be based on behavior, not syntax.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] The second hypothesis is called the *coupling effect*.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] The coupling effect asserts that simple faults can cascade or *couple* to form other emergent faults.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Subtle and important faults are also revealed by higher-order mutants, which further support the coupling effect.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Higher-order mutants are enabled by creating mutants with more than one mutation.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Mutation testing is done by selecting a set of mutation operators and then applying them to the source program one at a time for each applicable piece of the source code.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] The result of applying one mutation operator to the program is called a *mutant*.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] If the test suite is able to detect the change (i.e., one of the tests fails), then the mutant is said to be *killed*.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Test input data should *infect* the program state by causing different program states for the mutant and the original program.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] For example, a test with `a = 1` and `b = 0` would do this.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] The incorrect program state (the value of 'c') must *propagate* to the program's output and be checked by the test.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] These conditions are collectively called the *RIP model*.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] However, there are cases where it is not possible to find a test case that could kill this mutant.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] The resulting program is behaviorally equivalent to the original one.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Such mutants are called *equivalent mutants*.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Equivalent mutants detection is one of the biggest obstacles to practical usage of mutation testing.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] The effort needed to check if mutants are equivalent or not can be very high, even for small programs.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] A 2014 systematic literature review of a wide range of approaches to overcome the Equivalent Mutant Problem identified 17 relevant techniques (in 22 articles) and three categories of techniques: detecting (DEM); suggesting (SEM); and avoiding equivalent mutant generation (AEMG).
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] The experiment indicated that Higher Order Mutation in general and JudyDiffOp strategy in particular provide a promising approach to the Equivalent Mutant Problem.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] In addition to equivalent mutants, there are *subsumed mutants* which are mutants that exist in the same source code location as another mutant, and are said to be "subsumed" by the other mutant.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Subsumed mutants are not visible to a mutation testing tool, and do not contribute to coverage metrics.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] For example, let's say you have two mutants, A and B, that both change a line of code in the same way.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Mutant A is tested first, and the result is that the code is not working correctly.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Mutant B is then tested, and the result is the same as with mutant A.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] In this case, Mutant B is considered to be subsumed by Mutant A, since the result of testing Mutant B is the same as the result of testing Mutant A.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Therefore, Mutant B does not need to be tested, as the result will be the same as Mutant A.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] To make syntactic changes to a program, a mutation operator serves as a guideline that substitutes portions of the source code.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Given that mutations depend on these operators, scholars have created a collection of mutation operators to accommodate different programming languages, like Java.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] The effectiveness of these mutation operators plays a pivotal role in mutation testing.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Many mutation operators have been explored by researchers.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] These mutation operators are also called traditional mutation operators.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] There are also mutation operators for object-oriented languages, for concurrent constructions, complex objects like containers, etc.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Operators for containers are called *class-level* mutation operators.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Operators at the class level alter the program's structure by adding, removing, or changing the expressions being examined.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Specific operators have been established for each category of changes.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] For example, the muJava tool offers various class-level mutation operators such as Access Modifier Change, Type Cast Operator Insertion, and Type Cast Operator Deletion.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Mutation operators have also been developed to perform security vulnerability testing of programs.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Apart from the *class-level* operators, MuJava also includes *method-level* mutation operators, referred to as traditional operators.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] These traditional operators are designed based on features commonly found in procedural languages.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] They carry out changes to statements by adding, substituting, or removing primitive operators.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] These operators fall into six categories: *Arithmetic operators*, *Relational operator*s, *Conditional operators*, *Shift operators*, *Logical operators* and *Assignment operators*.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Statement mutation is a process where a block of code is intentionally modified by either deleting or copying certain statements.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Moreover, it allows for the reordering of statements within the code block to generate various sequences.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] This technique is crucial in software testing as it helps identify potential weaknesses or errors in the code.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] By deliberately making changes to the code and observing how it behaves, developers can uncover hidden bugs or flaws that might go unnoticed during regular testing.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Statement mutation is like a diagnostic tool that provides insights into the code's robustness and resilience, helping programmers improve the overall quality and reliability of their software.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Value mutation occurs when modifications are made to parameter or constant values within the code.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] This typically involves adjusting the values by adding or subtracting 1, but it can also involve making more substantial changes to the values.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Firstly, there's the transformation from a small value to a higher value.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] This entails replacing a small value in the code with a larger one.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] The purpose of this change is to assess how the code responds when it encounters larger inputs.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] It helps ensure that the code can accurately and efficiently process these larger values without encountering errors or unexpected issues.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Conversely, the second scenario involves changing a higher value to a smaller one.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] In this case, we replace a higher value within the code with a smaller value.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] This test aims to evaluate how the code handles smaller inputs.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Ensuring that the code performs correctly with smaller values is essential to prevent unforeseen problems or errors when dealing with such input data.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Decision mutation testing centers on the identification of design errors within the code, with a particular emphasis on detecting flaws or weaknesses in the program's decision-making logic.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] This method involves deliberately altering arithmetic and logical operators to expose potential issues.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] By manipulating these operators, developers can systematically evaluate how the code responds to different decision scenarios.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] This process helps ensure that the program's decision-making pathways are robust and accurate, preventing costly errors that could arise from faulty logic.
[src:mutation-testing/mutation-testing] Decision mutation testing serves as a valuable tool in software development, enabling developers to enhance the reliability and effectiveness of their decision-making code segments.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] Changes that may require regression testing include bug fixes, software enhancements, configuration changes, and even substitution of electronic components (hardware).
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] As regression test suites tend to grow with each found defect, test automation is frequently involved.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] Sometimes a change impact analysis is performed to determine an appropriate subset of tests (*non-regression analysis*).
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] As software is updated or changed, or reused on a modified target, emergence of new faults and/or re-emergence of old faults is quite common.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] Sometimes re-emergence occurs because a fix gets lost through poor revision control practices (or simple human error in revision control).
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] Often, a fix for a problem will be "fragile" in that it fixes the problem in the narrow case where it was first observed but not in more general cases which may arise over the lifetime of the software.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] Frequently, a fix for a problem in one area inadvertently causes a software bug in another area.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] It may happen that when a feature is redesigned some of the same mistakes that were made in the original implementation of the feature also occur in the redesign.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] In most software development situations, it is considered good coding practice, when a bug is located and fixed, to record a test that exposes the bug and re-run that test regularly after subsequent changes to the program.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] Although this may be done through manual testing procedures using programming techniques, it is often done using automated testing tools.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] Common strategies are to run such a system after every successful compile (for small projects), every night, or once a week.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] Those strategies can be automated by an external tool.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] Regression testing is an integral part of the extreme programming software development method.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] In this method, design documents are replaced by extensive, repeatable, and automated testing of the entire software package throughout each stage of the software development process.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] Regression testing is done after functional testing has concluded, to verify that the other functionalities are working.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] In the corporate world, regression testing has traditionally been performed by a software quality assurance team after the development team has completed work.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] However, defects found at this stage are the most costly to fix.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] This problem is being addressed by the rise of unit testing.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] Although developers have always written test cases as part of the development cycle, these test cases have generally been either functional tests or unit tests that verify only intended outcomes.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] Developer testing compels a developer to focus on unit testing and to include both positive and negative test cases.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] This technique checks all the test cases on the current program to check its integrity.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] Though it is expensive as it needs to re-run all the test cases, it ensures that there are no errors because of the modified code.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] Unlike Retest all, this technique runs a part of the test suite (owing to the cost of retest all) if the cost of selecting the part of the test suite is less than the Retest all technique.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] Prioritize the test cases so as to increase a test suite's rate of fault detection.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] Test case prioritization techniques schedule test cases so that the test cases that are higher in priority are executed before the test cases that have a lower priority.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] This technique is a hybrid of regression test selection and test case prioritization.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] Regression testing is performed when changes are made to the existing functionality of the software or if there is a bug fix in the software.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] Regression testing can be achieved through multiple approaches; if a *test all* approach is followed, it provides certainty that the changes made to the software have not affected the existing functionalities, which are unaltered.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] In agile software development—where the software development life cycles are very short, resources are scarce, and changes to the software are very frequent—regression testing might introduce a lot of unnecessary overhead.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] Regression testing can be used not only for testing the *correctness* of a program but often also for tracking the quality of its output.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] For instance, in the design of a compiler, regression testing could track the code size and the time it takes to compile and execute the test suite cases.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] — Fred Brooks, *The Mythical Man Month*, p.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] Regression tests can be done at any level, from unit through to system integration.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] Functional tests exercise the complete program with various inputs.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] These tests are often automated due to the need for repetition, and may be done by test tools that are not part of the compiler suite.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] Non-functional tests assess aspects such as performance, security, or reliability.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] Conducting non-functional regression tests presents additional challenges.
[src:mutation-testing/regression-testing] For example, detecting changes in performance is often statistically complex, while security issues typically arise from vulnerabilities in the software ecosystem rather than from individual code changes.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Software testing can provide objective, independent information about the quality of software and the risk of its failure to a user or sponsor or any other stakeholder.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Software testing can determine the correctness of software for specific scenarios but cannot determine correctness for all scenarios.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Based on the criteria for measuring correctness from an oracle, software testing employs principles and mechanisms that might recognize a problem.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Examples of oracles include specifications, contracts, comparable products, past versions of the same product, inferences about intended or expected purpose, user or customer expectations, relevant standards, and applicable laws.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Software testing can be functional or non-functional in nature.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Software testing is often dynamic in nature: running the software to verify actual output matches expected.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] It can also be static in nature: reviewing code and its associated documentation.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Software testing is often used to answer the question: Does the software do what it is supposed to do and what it needs to do?
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Information learned from software testing may be used to improve the process by which software is developed.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] A commonly suggested approach to automated testing is the "test pyramid," wherein most of the tests are unit tests, followed by a smaller set of integration tests and finally a few end-to-end (e2e) tests.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] A study conducted by NIST in 2002 reported that software bugs cost the U.S. economy $59.5 billion annually.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] More than a third of this cost could be avoided if better software testing was performed.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Outsourcing software testing because of costs is very common, with China, the Philippines, India and Pakistan being preferred destinations.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Myers initially introduced the separation of debugging from testing in 1979.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Although his attention was on breakage testing ("A successful test case is one that detects an as-yet undiscovered error."), it illustrated the desire of the software engineering community to separate fundamental development activities, such as debugging, from that of verification.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Software testing typically includes handling software bugs – a defect in the code that causes an undesirable result.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Bugs generally slow testing progress and involve programmer assistance to debug and fix.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] For example, a defect in dead code will not be considered a failure.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] A defect that does not cause failure at one point in time may lead to failure later due to environmental changes.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Examples of environment change include running on new computer hardware, changes in data, and interacting with different software.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Software testing is typically goal driven.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] A single defect may result in multiple failure symptoms.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Software testing may involve a Requirements gap – omission from the design for a requirement.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Requirement gaps can often be non-functional requirements such as testability, scalability, maintainability, performance, and security.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] A fundamental limitation of software testing is that testing under *all* combinations of inputs and preconditions (initial state) is not feasible, even with a simple product.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Defects that manifest in unusual conditions are difficult to find in testing.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Also, non-functional dimensions of quality (how it is supposed to *be* versus what it is supposed to *do*) – usability, scalability, performance, compatibility, and reliability – can be subjective; something that constitutes sufficient value to one person may not to another.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Although testing for every possible input is not feasible, testing can use combinatorics to maximize coverage while minimizing tests.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Test automation is the use of software (separate from the software being tested) for controlling the execution of tests and comparing actual outcome with predicted.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Test automation supports testing the system under test (SUT) without manual interaction which can lead to faster test execution and testing more often.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Test automation is a key aspect of continuous testing and often for continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD).
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Software testing can be categorized into levels based on how much of the software system is the focus of a test.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Unit testing, a.k.a. component or module testing, is a form of software testing by which isolated source code is tested to validate expected behavior.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Integration testing is a form of software testing in which multiple software components, modules, or services are tested together to verify they work as expected when combined.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] The focus is on testing the interactions and data exchange between integrated parts, rather than testing components in isolation.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] System testing, a.k.a. end-to-end (E2E) testing, is testing conducted on a complete software system.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] There are many approaches to software testing.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Reviews, walkthroughs, or inspections are referred to as static testing, whereas executing programmed code with a given set of test cases is referred to as dynamic testing.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Static testing is often implicit, like proofreading, plus when programming tools/text editors check source code structure or compilers (precompilers) check syntax and data flow as static program analysis.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Dynamic testing takes place when the program itself is run.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Dynamic testing may begin before the program is 100% complete in order to test particular sections of code and are applied to discrete functions or modules.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Typical techniques for these are either using stubs/drivers or execution from a debugger environment.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Static testing involves verification, whereas dynamic testing also involves validation.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Passive testing means verifying the system's behavior without any interaction with the software product.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Contrary to active testing, testers do not provide any test data but look at system logs and traces.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] They mine for patterns and specific behavior in order to make some kind of decisions.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] This is related to offline runtime verification and log analysis.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Exploratory testing is an approach to software testing that is concisely described as simultaneous learning, test design and test execution.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Software testing can often be divided into white-box and black-box.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] These two approaches are used to describe the point of view that the tester takes when designing test cases.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] A hybrid approach called grey-box that includes aspects of both boxes may also be applied to software testing methodology.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] White-box testing (also known as clear box testing, glass box testing, transparent box testing, and structural testing) verifies the internal structures or workings of a program, as opposed to the functionality exposed to the end-user.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] In white-box testing, an internal perspective of the system (the source code), as well as programming skills are used to design test cases.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] The tester chooses inputs to exercise paths through the code and determines the appropriate outputs.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] This is analogous to testing nodes in a circuit, e.g., in-circuit testing (ICT).
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] While white-box testing can be applied at the unit, integration, and system levels of the software testing process, it is usually done at the unit level.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] It can test paths within a unit, paths between units during integration, and between subsystems during a system–level test.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Though this method of test design can uncover many errors or problems, it might not detect unimplemented parts of the specification or missing requirements.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Code coverage tools can evaluate the completeness of a test suite that was created with any method, including black-box testing.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] This allows the software team to examine parts of a system that are rarely tested and ensures that the most important function points have been tested.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] 100% statement coverage ensures that all code paths or branches (in terms of control flow) are executed at least once.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] This is helpful in ensuring correct functionality, but not sufficient since the same code may process different inputs correctly or incorrectly.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Black-box testing (also known as functional testing) describes designing test cases without knowledge of the implementation, without reading the source code.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] The testers are only aware of what the software is supposed to do, not how it does it.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Black-box testing methods include: equivalence partitioning, boundary value analysis, all-pairs testing, state transition tables, decision table testing, fuzz testing, model-based testing, use case testing, exploratory testing, and specification-based testing.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Specification-based testing aims to test the functionality of software according to the applicable requirements.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] This level of testing usually requires thorough test cases to be provided to the tester, who then can simply verify that for a given input, the output value (or behavior), either "is" or "is not" the same as the expected value specified in the test case.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Test cases are built around specifications and requirements, i.e., what the application is supposed to do.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] It uses external descriptions of the software, including specifications, requirements, and designs, to derive test cases.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] These tests can be functional or non-functional, though usually functional.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Specification-based testing may be necessary to assure correct functionality, but it is insufficient to guard against complex or high-risk situations.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Black box testing can be used to any level of testing although usually not at the unit level.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Component interface testing is a variation of black-box testing, with the focus on the data values beyond just the related actions of a subsystem component.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] The practice of component interface testing can be used to check the handling of data passed between various units, or subsystem components, beyond full integration testing between those units.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] The data being passed can be considered as "message packets" and the range or data types can be checked for data generated from one unit and tested for validity before being passed into another unit.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] One option for interface testing is to keep a separate log file of data items being passed, often with a timestamp logged to allow analysis of thousands of cases of data passed between units for days or weeks.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Tests can include checking the handling of some extreme data values while other interface variables are passed as normal values.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Unusual data values in an interface can help explain unexpected performance in the next unit.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] The aim of visual testing is to provide developers with the ability to examine what was happening at the point of software failure by presenting the data in such a way that the developer can easily find the information he or she requires, and the information is expressed clearly.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] At the core of visual testing is the idea that showing someone a problem (or a test failure), rather than just describing it, greatly increases clarity and understanding.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Visual testing, therefore, requires the recording of the entire test process – capturing everything that occurs on the test system in video format.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Output videos are supplemented by real-time tester input via picture-in-a-picture webcam and audio commentary from microphones.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Visual testing provides a number of advantages.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] The quality of communication is increased drastically because testers can show the problem (and the events leading up to it) to the developer as opposed to just describing it, and the need to replicate test failures will cease to exist in many cases.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] The developer will have all the evidence he or she requires of a test failure and can instead focus on the cause of the fault and how it should be fixed.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Ad hoc testing and exploratory testing are important methodologies for checking software integrity because they require less preparation time to implement, while the important bugs can be found quickly.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] In ad hoc testing, where testing takes place in an improvised impromptu way, the ability of the tester(s) to base testing off documented methods and then improvise variations of those tests can result in a more rigorous examination of defect fixes.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] However, unless strict documentation of the procedures is maintained, one of the limits of ad hoc testing is lack of repeatability.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Grey-box testing (American spelling: gray-box testing) involves using knowledge of internal data structures and algorithms for purposes of designing tests while executing those tests at the user, or black-box level.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] The tester will often have access to both "the source code and the executable binary." Grey-box testing may also include reverse engineering (using dynamic code analysis) to determine, for instance, boundary values or error messages.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Manipulating input data and formatting output do not qualify as grey-box, as the input and output are clearly outside of the "black box" that we are calling the system under test.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] This distinction is particularly important when conducting integration testing between two modules of code written by two different developers, where only the interfaces are exposed for the test.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] By knowing the underlying concepts of how the software works, the tester makes better-informed testing choices while testing the software from outside.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Typically, a grey-box tester will be permitted to set up an isolated testing environment with activities, such as seeding a database.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] The tester can observe the state of the product being tested after performing certain actions such as executing SQL statements against the database and then executing queries to ensure that the expected changes have been reflected.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Grey-box testing implements intelligent test scenarios based on limited information.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] This will particularly apply to data type handling, exception handling, and so on.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] With the concept of grey-box testing, this "arbitrary distinction" between black- and white-box testing has faded somewhat.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Installation testing is a type of software testing that verifies that users can successfully install and set up software in its intended environments (e.g., operating systems, computer hardware).
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Most software systems have installation procedures that are needed before they can be used for their main purpose.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Installation testing focuses on these procedures and whether they're sufficient for achieving an installed, usable software system.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Procedures of this kind may involve full or partial upgrades, and install/uninstall processes.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] For example, in the case of a lack of backward compatibility, this can occur because the programmers develop and test software only on the latest version of the target environment, which not all users may be running.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] This results in the unintended consequence that the latest work may not function on earlier versions of the target environment, or on older hardware that earlier versions of the target environment were capable of using.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Sometimes such issues can be fixed by proactively abstracting operating system functionality into a separate program module or library.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Sanity testing determines whether it is reasonable to proceed with further testing.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Smoke testing consists of minimal attempts to operate the software, designed to determine whether there are any basic problems that will prevent it from working at all.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Such tests can be used as build verification test.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Regression testing focuses on finding defects after a major code change has occurred.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Specifically, it seeks to uncover software regressions, as degraded or lost features, including old bugs that have come back.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Such regressions occur whenever software functionality that was previously working correctly, stops working as intended.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Typically, regressions occur as an unintended consequence of program changes, when the newly developed part of the software collides with the previously existing code.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Common methods of regression testing include re-running previous sets of test cases and checking whether previously fixed faults have re-emerged.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] The depth of testing depends on the phase in the release process and the risk of the added features.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] They can either be complete, for changes added late in the release or deemed to be risky, or be very shallow, consisting of positive tests on each feature, if the changes are early in the release or deemed to be of low risk.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Acceptance testing is system-level testing to ensure the software meets customer expectations.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Acceptance testing may be performed at the end or in the middle of a project, including after each completed user story in an agile project.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Tests are frequently grouped into these levels by where they are performed in the software development process, or by the level of specificity of the test.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Sometimes, UAT is performed by the customer, in their environment and on their own hardware.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] OAT is used to conduct operational readiness (prerelease) of a product, service or system as part of a quality management system.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] OAT is a common type of non-functional software testing, used mainly in software development and software maintenance projects.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] This type of testing focuses on the operational readiness of the system to be supported, or to become part of the production environment.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Hence, it is also known as operational readiness testing (ORT) or operations readiness and assurance (OR&A) testing.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Functional testing within OAT is limited to those tests that are required to verify the *non-functional* aspects of the system.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] In addition, the software testing should ensure that the portability of the system, as well as working as expected, does not also damage or partially corrupt its operating environment or cause other processes within that environment to become inoperative.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Contractual acceptance testing is performed based on the contract's acceptance criteria defined during the agreement of the contract, while regulatory acceptance testing is performed based on the relevant regulations to the software product.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Both of these two tests can be performed by users or independent testers.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Regulation acceptance testing sometimes involves the regulatory agencies auditing the test results.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Alpha testing is simulated or actual operational testing by potential users/customers or an independent test team at the developers' site.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Alpha testing is often employed for off-the-shelf software as a form of internal acceptance testing before the software goes to beta testing.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Beta testing comes after alpha testing and can be considered a form of external user acceptance testing.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Versions of the software, known as beta versions, are released to a limited audience outside of the programming team known as beta testers.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] The software is released to groups of people so that further testing can ensure the product has few faults or bugs.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Beta versions can be made available to the open public to increase the feedback field to a maximal number of future users and to deliver value earlier, for an extended or even indefinite period of time (perpetual beta).
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Functional testing refers to activities that verify a specific action or function of the code.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] These are usually found in the code requirements documentation, although some development methodologies work from use cases or user stories.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Non-functional testing refers to aspects of the software that may not be related to a specific function or user action, such as scalability or other performance, behavior under certain constraints, or security.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Testing will determine the breaking point, the point at which extremes of scalability or performance leads to unstable execution.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Non-functional requirements tend to be those that reflect the quality of the product, particularly in the context of the suitability perspective of its users.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Continuous testing is the process of executing automated tests as part of the software delivery pipeline to obtain immediate feedback on the business risks associated with a software release candidate.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Continuous testing includes the validation of both functional requirements and non-functional requirements; the scope of testing extends from validating bottom-up requirements or user stories to assessing the system requirements associated with overarching business goals.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Destructive testing attempts to cause the software or a sub-system to fail.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] It verifies whether the software functions properly when it receives invalid or unexpected inputs, thereby assessing the robustness of input validation and error-management routines.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Software fault injection, in the form of fuzzing, is an example of failure testing.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Various commercial non-functional testing tools are linked from the software fault injection page; there are also numerous open-source and free software tools available that perform destructive testing.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Performance testing is generally executed to determine how a system or sub-system performs in terms of responsiveness and stability under a particular workload.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] It can also serve to investigate, measure, validate or verify other quality attributes of the system, such as scalability, reliability and resource usage.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] There is little agreement on what the specific goals of performance testing are.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] The terms load testing, performance testing, scalability testing, and volume testing, are often used interchangeably.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Real-time software systems have strict timing constraints.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] To test if timing constraints are met, real-time testing is used.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Usability testing is to check if the user interface is easy to use and understand.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] It is concerned mainly with the use of the application.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] This is not a kind of testing that can be automated; actual human users are needed, being monitored by skilled UI designers.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Usability testing can use structured models to check how well an interface works.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] The Stanton, Theofanos, and Joshi (2015) model looks at user experience, and the Al-Sharafat and Qadoumi (2016) model is for expert evaluation, helping to assess usability in digital applications.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Accessibility testing is done to ensure that the software is accessible to persons with disabilities.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Security testing is essential for software that processes confidential data to prevent system intrusion by hackers.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Testing for internationalization and localization validates that the software can be used with different languages and geographic regions.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] The process of pseudolocalization is used to test the ability of an application to be translated to another language, and make it easier to identify when the localization process may introduce new bugs into the product.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Globalization testing verifies that the software is adapted for a new culture, such as different currencies or time zones.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Actual translation to human languages must be tested, too.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Development testing is a software development process that involves the synchronized application of a broad spectrum of defect prevention and detection strategies in order to reduce software development risks, time, and costs.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] It is performed by the software developer or engineer during the construction phase of the software development lifecycle.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Development testing aims to eliminate construction errors before code is promoted to other testing; this strategy is intended to increase the quality of the resulting software as well as the efficiency of the overall development process.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Depending on the organization's expectations for software development, development testing might include static code analysis, data flow analysis, metrics analysis, peer code reviews, unit testing, code coverage analysis, traceability, and other software testing practices.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] A/B testing is a method of running a controlled experiment to determine if a proposed change is more effective than the current approach.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Customers are routed to either a current version (control) of a feature, or to a modified version (treatment) and data is collected to determine which version is better at achieving the desired outcome.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Concurrent or concurrency testing assesses the behaviour and performance of software and systems that use concurrent computing, generally under normal usage conditions.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Typical problems this type of testing will expose are deadlocks, race conditions and problems with shared memory/resource handling.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] In software testing, conformance testing verifies that a product performs according to its specified standards.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Compilers, for instance, are extensively tested to determine whether they meet the recognized standard for that language.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] For example, every output from a serialization function should be accepted by the corresponding deserialization function, and every output from a sort function should be a monotonically increasing list containing exactly the same elements as its input.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Property testing libraries allow the user to control the strategy by which random inputs are constructed, to ensure coverage of degenerate cases, or inputs featuring specific patterns that are needed to fully exercise aspects of the implementation under test.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Property testing is also sometimes known as "generative testing" or "QuickCheck testing" since it was introduced and popularized by the Haskell library QuickCheck.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Metamorphic testing (MT) is a property-based software testing technique, which can be an effective approach for addressing the test oracle problem and test case generation problem.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] The test oracle problem is the difficulty of determining the expected outcomes of selected test cases or to determine whether the actual outputs agree with the expected outcomes.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] VCR testing, also known as "playback testing" or "record/replay" testing, is a testing technique for increasing the reliability and speed of regression tests that involve a component that is slow or unreliable to communicate with, often a third-party API outside of the tester's control.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] It involves making a recording ("cassette") of the system's interactions with the external component, and then replaying the recorded interactions as a substitute for communicating with the external system on subsequent runs of the test.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] The technique was popularized in web development by the Ruby library vcr.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] It is often used in the context of distributed systems, service-oriented software architectures, and microservices.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Since the early 2020s, artificial intelligence has increasingly been integrated into software testing workflows.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] AI-driven testing methods automate the creation of test cases, dynamically adapt to changes, and leverage machine learning to identify high-risk areas of the codebase — an approach that enhances regression testing efficiency while expanding overall test coverage.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] A key development is **self-healing test automation**, in which automated tests automatically detect and adapt to changes in a user interface without human intervention.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Studies of AI-driven test automation across over 3,600 grey literature sources identified self-healing test scripts as one of the most common AI solutions in practice.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] A case study presented at the 2023 International Conference on Information Management and Technology (ICIMTech) found that integrating shift-left testing into an agile development methodology over one year measurably reduced the number of bugs reaching production.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] In an organization, testers may be in a separate team from the rest of the software development team or they may be integrated into one team.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Software testing can also be performed by non-dedicated software testers.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] In the 1980s, the term *software tester* started to be used to denote a separate profession.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Notable software testing roles and titles include: *test manager*, *test lead*, *test analyst*, *test designer*, *tester*, *automation developer*, and *test administrator*.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Organizations that develop software, perform testing differently, but there are common patterns.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] In waterfall development, testing is generally performed after the code is completed, but before the product is shipped to the customer.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] This practice often results in the testing phase being used as a project buffer to compensate for project delays, thereby compromising the time devoted to testing.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Some contend that the waterfall process allows for testing to start when the development project starts and to be a continuous process until the project finishes.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Agile software development commonly involves testing while the code is being written and organizing teams with both programmers and testers and with team members performing both programming and testing.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] One agile practice, test-driven software development (TDD), is a way of unit testing such that unit-level testing is performed while writing the product code.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Test code is updated as new features are added and failure conditions are discovered (bugs fixed).
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Commonly, the unit test code is maintained with the project code, integrated in the build process, and run on each build and as part of regression testing.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Goals of this continuous integration is to support development and reduce defects.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] Even in organizations that separate teams by programming and testing functions, many often have the programmers perform unit testing.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] The sample below is common for waterfall development.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p01] The same activities are commonly found in other development models, but might be described differently.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] The terms verification and validation are commonly used interchangeably in the industry; it is also common to see these two terms defined with contradictory definitions.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] Verification is the process of evaluating a system or component to determine whether the products of a given development phase satisfy the conditions imposed at the start of that phase.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] Validation is the process of evaluating a system or component during or at the end of the development process to determine whether it satisfies specified requirements.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] Verification is confirmation by examination and through provision of objective evidence that specified requirements have been fulfilled.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] Validation is confirmation by examination and through provision of objective evidence that the requirements for a specific intended use or application have been fulfilled.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] The contradiction is caused by the use of the concepts of requirements and specified requirements but with different meanings.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] In the case of IEEE standards, the specified requirements, mentioned in the definition of validation, are the set of problems, needs and wants of the stakeholders that the software must solve and satisfy.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] Such requirements are documented in a Software Requirements Specification (SRS).
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] And, the products mentioned in the definition of verification, are the output artifacts of every phase of the software development process.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] These products are, in fact, specifications such as Architectural Design Specification, Detailed Design Specification, etc.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] The SRS is also a specification, but it cannot be verified (at least not in the sense used here – more on this subject below).
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] But, for the ISO 9000, the specified requirements are the set of specifications, as just mentioned above, that must be verified.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] A specification, as previously explained, is the product of a software development process phase that receives another specification as input.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] A specification is verified successfully when it correctly implements its input specification.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] All the specifications can be verified except the SRS because it is the first one (it can be validated, though).
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] An example scenario be that the Design Specification must implement the SRS, and the Construction phase artifacts must implement the Design Specification.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] So, when these words are defined in common terms, the apparent contradiction disappears.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] Both the SRS and the software must be validated.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] The SRS can be validated statically by consulting with the stakeholders.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] Nevertheless, running some partial implementation of the software or a prototype of any kind (dynamic testing) and obtaining positive feedback from them, can further increase the certainty that the SRS is correctly formulated.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] On the other hand, the software, as a final and running product (not its artifacts and documents, including the source code) must be validated dynamically with the stakeholders by executing the software and having them to try it.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] Some might argue that, for SRS, the input is the words of stakeholders and, therefore, SRS validation is the same as SRS verification.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] Thinking this way is not advisable as it only causes more confusion.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] It is better to think of verification as a process involving a formal and technical input document.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] In some organizations, software testing is part of a software quality assurance (SQA) process.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] In SQA, software process specialists and auditors are concerned with the software development process rather than just the artifacts such as documentation, code and systems.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] They examine and change the software engineering process itself to reduce the number of faults that end up in the delivered software: the so-called defect rate.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] What constitutes an acceptable defect rate depends on the nature of the software; a flight simulator video game would have much higher defect tolerance than software for an actual airplane.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] Although there are close links with SQA, testing departments often exist independently, and there may be no SQA function in some companies.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] Software testing is an activity to investigate software under test in order to provide quality-related information to stakeholders.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] By contrast, QA (quality assurance) is the implementation of policies and procedures intended to prevent defects from reaching customers.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] Quality measures include such topics as correctness, completeness, security and ISO/IEC 9126 requirements such as capability, reliability, efficiency, portability, maintainability, compatibility, and usability.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] There are a number of frequently used software metrics, or measures, which are used to assist in determining the state of the software or the adequacy of the testing.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] A software testing process can produce several artifacts.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] The actual artifacts produced are a factor of the software development model used, stakeholder and organisational needs.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] A test plan is a document detailing the approach that will be taken for intended test activities.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] The plan may include aspects such as objectives, scope, processes and procedures, personnel requirements, and contingency plans.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] The test plan could come in the form of a single plan that includes all test types (like an acceptance or system test plan) and planning considerations, or it may be issued as a master test plan that provides an overview of more than one detailed test plan (a plan of a plan).
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] A test plan can be, in some cases, part of a wide "test strategy" which documents overall testing approaches, which may itself be a master test plan or even a separate artifact.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] In software development, a traceability matrix (TM) is a document, usually in the form of a table, used to assist in determining the completeness of a relationship by correlating any two baselined documents using a many-to-many relationship comparison.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] It is often used with high-level requirements (these often consist of marketing requirements) and detailed requirements of the product to the matching parts of high-level design, detailed design, test plan, and test cases.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] A test case normally consists of a unique identifier, requirement references from a design specification, preconditions, events, a series of steps (also known as actions) to follow, input, output, expected result, and the actual result.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] Clinically defined, a test case is an input and an expected result.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] This can be as terse as "for condition x your derived result is y", although normally test cases describe in more detail the input scenario and what results might be expected.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] It can occasionally be a series of steps (but often steps are contained in a separate test procedure that can be exercised against multiple test cases, as a matter of economy) but with one expected result or expected outcome.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] The optional fields are a test case ID, test step, or order of execution number, related requirement(s), depth, test category, author, and check boxes for whether the test is automatable and has been automated.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] Larger test cases may also contain prerequisite states or steps, and descriptions.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] A test case should also contain a place for the actual result.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] These steps can be stored in a word processor document, spreadsheet, database, or other common repositories.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] In a database system, you may also be able to see past test results, who generated the results, and what system configuration was used to generate those results.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] These past results would usually be stored in a separate table.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] A test script is a procedure or programming code that replicates user actions.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] Initially, the term was derived from the product of work created by automated regression test tools.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] A test case will be a baseline to create test scripts using a tool or a program.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] In software development, a test suite, less commonly known as a validation suite, is a collection of test cases that are intended to be used to test a software program to show that it has some specified set of behaviors.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] A test suite often contains detailed instructions or goals for each collection of test cases and information on the system configuration to be used during testing.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] A group of test cases may also contain prerequisite states or steps and descriptions of the following tests.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] In most cases, multiple sets of values or data are used to test the same functionality of a particular feature.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] All the test values and changeable environmental components are collected in separate files and stored as test data.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] It is also useful to provide this data to the client and with the product or a project.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] There are techniques to generate Test data.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] The software, tools, samples of data input and output, and configurations are all referred to collectively as a test harness.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] A test run is a collection of test cases or test suites that the user is executing and comparing the expected with the actual results.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] Once complete, a report or all executed tests may be generated.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] Several certification programs exist to support the professional aspirations of software testers and quality assurance specialists.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] A few practitioners argue that the testing field is not ready for certification, as mentioned in the controversy section.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] is so expensive relative to its value that it should be used sparingly.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] The test automation then can be considered as a way to capture and implement the requirements.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] As a general rule, the larger the system and the greater the complexity, the greater the ROI in test automation.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] Also, the investment in tools and expertise can be amortized over multiple projects with the right level of knowledge sharing within an organization.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] Significant opposition has formed out of the ranks of the context-driven school of software testing about the ISO 29119 standard.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] Professional testing associations, such as the International Society for Software Testing, have attempted to have the standard withdrawn.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] No certification now offered actually requires the applicant to show their ability to test software.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] No certification is based on a widely accepted body of knowledge.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] Certification itself cannot measure an individual's productivity, their skill, or practical knowledge, and cannot guarantee their competence, or professionalism as a tester.
[src:mutation-testing/software-testing-p02] There are opposing views on the applicability of studies used to show the relative expense of fixing defects depending on their introduction and detection.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Unit testing describes tests that are run at the unit-level to contrast testing at the integration or system level.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Unit testing, as a principle for testing separately smaller parts of large software systems, dates back to the early days of software engineering.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] In June 1956 at US Navy's Symposium on Advanced Programming Methods for Digital Computers, H.D.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] It featured a specification-based approach where the coding phase was followed by "parameter testing" to validate component subprograms against their specification, followed then by an "assembly testing" for parts put together.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] In 1964, a similar approach is described for the software of the Mercury project, where individual units developed by different programmers underwent "unit tests" before being integrated together.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] In 1969, testing methodologies appear more structured, with unit tests, component tests and integration tests collectively validating individual parts written separately and their progressive assembly into larger blocks.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Some public standards adopted in the late 1960s, such as MIL-STD-483 and MIL-STD-490, contributed further to a wide acceptance of unit testing in large projects.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Unit testing was in those times interactive or automated, using either coded tests or capture and replay testing tools.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] In 1989, Kent Beck described a testing framework for Smalltalk (later called SUnit) in "Simple Smalltalk Testing: With Patterns".
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] In 1997, Kent Beck and Erich Gamma developed and released JUnit, a unit test framework that became popular with Java developers.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Google embraced automated testing around 2005–2006.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] A unit is defined as a single behaviour exhibited by the system under test (SUT), usually corresponding to a requirement.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] While a unit may correspond to a single function or module (in procedural programming) or a single method or class (in object-oriented programming), functions/methods and modules/classes do not necessarily correspond to units.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] From the system requirements perspective only the perimeter of the system is relevant, thus only entry points to externally visible system behaviours define units.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Unit tests can be performed manually or via automated test execution.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Automated tests include benefits such as: running tests often, running tests without staffing cost, and consistent and repeatable testing.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Testing is often performed by the programmer who writes and modifies the code under test.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Unit testing may be viewed as part of the process of writing code.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] During development, a programmer may code criteria, or results that are known to be good, into the test to verify the unit's correctness.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] During test execution, frameworks log tests that fail any criterion and report them in a summary.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] For this, the most commonly used approach is test - function - expected value.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Test cases underlie testing that is methodical rather than haphazard.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] A battery of test cases can be built to produce the desired coverage of the software being tested.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Formally defined test cases allow the same tests to be run repeatedly against successive versions of the software, allowing for effective and consistent regression testing.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] A test double is software used in software test automation that satisfies a dependency so that the test need not depend on production code.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] A test double provides functionality via an interface that the software under test cannot distinguish from production code.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] A parameterized test is a test that accepts a set of values that can be used to enable the test to run with multiple, different input values.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] A testing framework that supports parametrized tests supports a way to encode parameter sets and to run the test with each set.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Use of parametrized tests can reduce test code duplication.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Parameterized tests are supported by TestNG, JUnit, XUnit and NUnit, as well as in various JavaScript test frameworks.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Parameters for the unit tests may be coded manually or in some cases are automatically generated by the test framework.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] In recent years support was added for writing more powerful (unit) tests, leveraging the concept of theories, test cases that execute the same steps, but using test data generated at runtime, unlike regular parameterized tests that use the same execution steps with input sets that are pre-defined.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Test code needs access to the code it is testing, but testing should not compromise normal design goals such as information hiding, encapsulation and the separation of concerns.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] To enable access to code not exposed in the external API, unit tests can be located in the same project or module as the code being tested.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] In object oriented design this still may not provide access to private data and methods.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Therefore, extra work may be necessary for unit tests.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] In Java and other languages, a developer can use reflection to access private fields and methods.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Alternatively, an inner class can be used to hold the unit tests so they have visibility of the enclosing class's members and attributes.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] In the .NET Framework and some other programming languages, partial classes may be used to expose private methods and data for the tests to access.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] It is important that code solely for accommodating tests does not remain in the production code.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] In C and other languages, compiler directives such as `#if DEBUG ... #endif` can be placed around such additional classes and indeed all other test-related code to prevent them being compiled into the released code.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] This means the released code is not exactly the same as what was unit tested.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] The regular running of fewer but more comprehensive, end-to-end, integration tests on the final release build can ensure (among other things) that no production code exists that subtly relies on aspects of the test harness.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] There is some debate among developers, as to whether it is wise to test private methods and data anyway.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Some argue that private members are a mere implementation detail that may change, and should be allowed to do so without breaking numbers of tests.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Thus it should be sufficient to test any class through its public interface or through its subclass interface, which some languages call the "protected" interface.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Others say that crucial aspects of functionality may be implemented in private methods and testing them directly offers advantage of smaller and more direct unit tests.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] In test-driven development (TDD), unit tests are written before the related production code is written.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Starting with a failing test, then adds *just enough* production code to make the test pass, then refactors the code as makes sense and then repeats by adding another failing test.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Unit testing is intended to ensure that the units meet their design and behave as intended.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] By writing tests first for the smallest testable units, then the compound behaviors between those, one can build up comprehensive tests for complex applications.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] One goal of unit testing is to isolate each part of the program and show that the individual parts are correct.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] A unit test provides a strict, written contract that the piece of code must satisfy.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Unit testing finds problems early in the development cycle.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] This includes both bugs in the programmer's implementation and flaws or missing parts of the specification for the unit.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] The process of writing a thorough set of tests forces the author to think through inputs, outputs, and error conditions, and thus more crisply define the unit's desired behavior.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] The cost of finding a bug before coding begins or when the code is first written is considerably lower than the cost of detecting, identifying, and correcting the bug later.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Bugs in released code may also cause costly problems for the end-users of the software.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Code can be impossible or difficult to unit test if poorly written, thus unit testing can force developers to structure functions and objects in better ways.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Unit testing enables more frequent releases in software development.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] By testing individual components in isolation, developers can quickly identify and address issues, leading to faster iteration and release cycles.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Unit testing allows the programmer to refactor code or upgrade system libraries at a later date, and make sure the module still works correctly (e.g., in regression testing).
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] The procedure is to write test cases for all functions and methods so that whenever a change causes a fault, it can be identified quickly.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Unit tests detect changes which may break a design contract.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Unit testing may reduce uncertainty in the units themselves and can be used in a bottom-up testing style approach.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] By testing the parts of a program first and then testing the sum of its parts, integration testing becomes much easier.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Some programmers contend that unit tests provide a form of documentation of the code.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Developers wanting to learn what functionality is provided by a unit, and how to use it, can review the unit tests to gain an understanding of it.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Test cases can embody characteristics that are critical to the success of the unit.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] These characteristics can indicate appropriate/inappropriate use of a unit as well as negative behaviors that are to be trapped by the unit.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] A test case documents these critical characteristics, although many software development environments do not rely solely upon code to document the product in development.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] In some processes, the act of writing tests and the code under test, plus associated refactoring, may take the place of formal design.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Each unit test can be seen as a design element specifying classes, methods, and observable behavior.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Testing will not catch every error in the program, because it cannot evaluate every execution path in any but the most trivial programs.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] This problem is a superset of the halting problem, which is undecidable.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Additionally, unit testing by definition only tests the functionality of the units themselves.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Therefore, it will not catch integration errors or broader system-level errors (such as functions performed across multiple units, or non-functional test areas such as performance).
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Unit testing should be done in conjunction with other software testing activities, as they can only show the presence or absence of particular errors; they cannot prove a complete absence of errors.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] To guarantee correct behavior for every execution path and every possible input, and ensure the absence of errors, other techniques are required, namely the application of formal methods to prove that a software component has no unexpected behavior.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] An elaborate hierarchy of unit tests does not equal integration testing.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Integration with peripheral units should be included in integration tests, but not in unit tests.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Integration testing typically still relies heavily on humans testing manually; high-level or global-scope testing can be difficult to automate, such that manual testing often appears faster and cheaper.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Software testing is a combinatorial problem.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] For example, every Boolean decision statement requires at least two tests: one with an outcome of "true" and one with an outcome of "false".
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] As a result, for every line of code written, programmers often need 3 to 5 lines of test code.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] This obviously takes time and its investment may not be worth the effort.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] There are problems that cannot easily be tested at all – for example those that are nondeterministic or involve multiple threads.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] In addition, code for a unit test is as likely to be buggy as the code it is testing.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Another challenge related to writing the unit tests is the difficulty of setting up realistic and useful tests.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] It is necessary to create relevant initial conditions so the part of the application being tested behaves like part of the complete system.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] If these initial conditions are not set correctly, the test will not be exercising the code in a realistic context, which diminishes the value and accuracy of unit test results.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] To obtain the intended benefits from unit testing, rigorous discipline is needed throughout the software development process.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] It is essential to keep careful records not only of the tests that have been performed, but also of all changes that have been made to the source code of this or any other unit in the software.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Use of a version control system is essential.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] If a later version of the unit fails a particular test that it had previously passed, the version-control software can provide a list of the source code changes (if any) that have been applied to the unit since that time.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] It is also essential to implement a sustainable process for ensuring that test case failures are reviewed regularly and addressed immediately.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] If such a process is not implemented and ingrained into the team's workflow, the application will evolve out of sync with the unit test suite, increasing false positives and reducing the effectiveness of the test suite.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Unit testing embedded system software presents challenges because the software is being developed on a different platform than the one it will eventually run on, making it difficult to run a test program in the actual deployment environment, as is possible with desktop programs.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] Unit tests tend to be easiest when a method has input parameters and some output.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] It is not as easy to create unit tests when a major function of the method is to interact with something external to the application.
[src:mutation-testing/unit-testing] For example, a method that will work with a database might require a mock up of database interactions to be created, which probably won't be as comprehensive as the real database interactions.
